00:45:11.360 --> 00:45:13.790
I was wondering if you
could speak briefly

00:45:13.790 --> 00:45:19.850
about the standards
of evidence on paper

00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:22.760
needing to be overwhelming
to convict someone.

00:45:22.760 --> 00:45:24.980
To get a conviction
thrown out, do

00:45:24.980 --> 00:45:28.520
you just need to establish
a reasonable doubt?

00:45:28.520 --> 00:45:32.150
Or are the standards equally
high, or is it even harder

00:45:32.150 --> 00:45:34.640
to get something
overturned than it is

00:45:34.640 --> 00:45:36.595
to get the original conviction?

00:45:36.595 --> 00:45:38.470
BARRY SCHECK: It's very
hard to get something

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:41.580
overturned in most states--

00:45:41.580 --> 00:45:45.250
I think, in actually just
about every state right now.

00:45:45.250 --> 00:45:47.720
And it wasn't always true.

00:45:47.720 --> 00:45:52.810
There are statutes that
say that a state must

00:45:52.810 --> 00:45:57.790
have a mechanism whereby
new evidence of innocence

00:45:57.790 --> 00:46:01.600
can be brought forward so that
a conviction can be vacated.

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:06.850
In most states, the standard
is a reasonable probability

00:46:06.850 --> 00:46:08.560
of a different outcome.

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:11.560
The problem when you talk
about newly discovered evidence

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:15.730
like that is they define newly
discovered evidence as evidence

00:46:15.730 --> 00:46:19.020
that couldn't have been
found with the exercise

00:46:19.020 --> 00:46:22.210
of due diligence by
the defense lawyer.

00:46:22.210 --> 00:46:26.200
So there's plenty of stuff
that lawyers don't find.

00:46:26.200 --> 00:46:28.260
We won't go on at any
great length about it,

00:46:28.260 --> 00:46:32.720
but Kevin's lawyer was
not up to the task.

00:46:32.720 --> 00:46:34.570
And in the middle
of the trial, they

00:46:34.570 --> 00:46:36.370
substituted in a new lawyer.

00:46:36.370 --> 00:46:38.050
All right.

00:46:38.050 --> 00:46:40.880
This case would have been
hard under any circumstances,

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:42.700
but when you go
back and look at it,

00:46:42.700 --> 00:46:46.130
there was plenty of information,
particularly the time

00:46:46.130 --> 00:46:47.980
line, that raised doubts.

00:46:47.980 --> 00:46:50.950
Even some jurors in this
case held out for a while,

00:46:50.950 --> 00:46:53.230
because they said,
wow, not withstanding

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:55.810
the publicity and the
terrible way this looks,

00:46:55.810 --> 00:46:57.950
we see problems in this case.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:47:00.820
So reasonable probability
of a different outcome

00:47:00.820 --> 00:47:02.110
is usually the standard.

00:47:02.110 --> 00:47:04.870
In some states, it's clear
and convincing evidence

00:47:04.870 --> 00:47:05.980
of innocence.

00:47:05.980 --> 00:47:08.410
But the problem that we've
had in the United States

00:47:08.410 --> 00:47:11.770
is that after a certain
number of years, sometimes

00:47:11.770 --> 00:47:13.540
you can't get back into court.

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:16.000
It is very, very, very hard.

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:19.030
And also, if you want to
claim ineffective assistance

00:47:19.030 --> 00:47:19.630
of counsel--

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:23.920
and this is something that
is very, very troubling--

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:25.750
the standard for
ineffective assistance

00:47:25.750 --> 00:47:28.360
of counsel, Peter
Neufeld and I sometimes

00:47:28.360 --> 00:47:30.820
say jokingly and our
colleagues in the movement,

00:47:30.820 --> 00:47:33.010
if you put a mirror under
the nose of the lawyer

00:47:33.010 --> 00:47:36.670
and it fogs up, that's an
effective lawyer, right?

00:47:36.670 --> 00:47:39.940
It's very, very hard to reverse
convictions on that ground.

00:47:39.940 --> 00:47:42.640
And one of the reasons
is that they say, well,

00:47:42.640 --> 00:47:43.960
the standard is--

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:46.420
what are the likely
errors and omissions

00:47:46.420 --> 00:47:52.210
of lawyers in a community
like you're practicing.

00:47:52.210 --> 00:47:54.400
And that is defined as too low.

00:47:54.400 --> 00:47:56.170
There should be a
national objective

00:47:56.170 --> 00:47:59.050
norm of what constitutes
effective assistance

00:47:59.050 --> 00:48:00.230
of counsel.

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:03.460
There are jurisdictions all
across this country where

00:48:03.460 --> 00:48:05.170
you show up the
first time in court,

00:48:05.170 --> 00:48:07.060
there's no lawyers there, right?

00:48:07.060 --> 00:48:10.150
People plead guilty
all the time.

00:48:10.150 --> 00:48:13.480
We have many, many
great public defenders.

00:48:13.480 --> 00:48:18.790
But in general, in terms of
all criminal justice reform,

00:48:18.790 --> 00:48:24.520
in my opinion, the least
effective reform movement

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:28.270
now is getting
funds to represent

00:48:28.270 --> 00:48:30.010
people charged with crimes.

00:48:30.010 --> 00:48:32.230
And it is really the
key, because if we

00:48:32.230 --> 00:48:34.330
want to deal with
mass incarceration,

00:48:34.330 --> 00:48:37.930
and you want to have a way to
get people who are mentally

00:48:37.930 --> 00:48:40.420
ill out of this system, people
who have substance abuse

00:48:40.420 --> 00:48:44.440
problems out of the system,
people that have family

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:46.190
violence problems
out of the system

00:48:46.190 --> 00:48:49.570
and effectively treated,
to know who should get bail

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:52.750
and who shouldn't, to
have a fair sentencing,

00:48:52.750 --> 00:48:54.520
it's got to be individualized.

00:48:54.520 --> 00:48:56.920
How can that really
be done unless you

00:48:56.920 --> 00:49:00.580
have defense lawyers that
know not just the defendant,

00:49:00.580 --> 00:49:01.920
but the whole family?

00:49:01.920 --> 00:49:06.220
That knew Kevin was raised
by women, that his mother was

00:49:06.220 --> 00:49:10.030
from Richmond, that knew the
whole family context, that

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:11.210
knew everything.

00:49:11.210 --> 00:49:12.730
You don't have that
in this country,

00:49:12.730 --> 00:49:16.960
because we don't give
money sufficiently to those

00:49:16.960 --> 00:49:19.360
who are representing the poor.

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:22.030
And a lot of it has to do
with structural racism,

00:49:22.030 --> 00:49:25.480
but we need a Marshall
Plan for indigent defense

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:26.390
in this country.

00:49:26.390 --> 00:49:29.320
That's what we need, and we
need to have it working together

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:31.250
with all the stakeholders.

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:36.460
So even if I told you we could
change the legal standard,

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:38.170
we'd still need
lawyers to get it done.

