issues, are terrific,

00:56:58.100 --> 00:56:59.360
like the Marshall Project.

00:56:59.360 --> 00:57:00.860
I highly recommend that.

00:57:00.860 --> 00:57:03.150
Those of us in the criminal
justice reform movement,

00:57:03.150 --> 00:57:05.900
we get up in the morning, we
look at the Marshall Project.

00:57:05.900 --> 00:57:08.300
But what I want to
commend to your attention

00:57:08.300 --> 00:57:10.730
about the Marshall
Project is the person

00:57:10.730 --> 00:57:13.120
who really started it
is Bill Keller, who

00:57:13.120 --> 00:57:15.320
was an editor of
"The New York Times."

00:57:15.320 --> 00:57:18.020
And all the people that are
involved in the Marshall

00:57:18.020 --> 00:57:21.620
Project and other journalists
that they bring in

00:57:21.620 --> 00:57:26.210
to write articles,
they care about facts.

00:57:26.210 --> 00:57:28.280
They care about what's truthful.

00:57:28.280 --> 00:57:30.500
They'll be politically
incorrect when

00:57:30.500 --> 00:57:34.010
it comes to looking at
solutions to the problems.

00:57:34.010 --> 00:57:38.960
I think it's great that there
are all kinds of other websites

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:43.370
that can do this and
investigative teams

00:57:43.370 --> 00:57:46.460
like the people at ProPublica.

00:57:46.460 --> 00:57:49.370
It's a heyday now
for publications,

00:57:49.370 --> 00:57:52.640
like "The Atlantic" have
been terrific and of course,

00:57:52.640 --> 00:57:54.890
"The New Yorker"
and others that will

00:57:54.890 --> 00:57:58.520
do deep dives and
investigative reports.

00:57:58.520 --> 00:58:02.480
But what's so important
now is that we have

00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:05.570
to stop being so tribalized.

00:58:05.570 --> 00:58:10.400
You really have to search
the web and look for facts.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:13.100
And I'm hopeful-- we
don't have it now,

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:16.280
but I'm hopeful that
what will happen

00:58:16.280 --> 00:58:21.242
is that we will begin to
get authoritative voices,

00:58:21.242 --> 00:58:23.450
whether they're on the left
or the right or anywhere,

00:58:23.450 --> 00:58:28.550
where you will have some
assurance that what I'm seeing

00:58:28.550 --> 00:58:33.410
online here so quickly has
actually been fact checked,

00:58:33.410 --> 00:58:36.870
that responsible people
are doing the research,

00:58:36.870 --> 00:58:40.820
so we'll get some confidence
in the truth of what's

00:58:40.820 --> 00:58:42.350
being reported.

00:58:42.350 --> 00:58:45.470
These democratic
rights that we have--

00:58:45.470 --> 00:58:48.470
the presumption of innocence,
trial by jury, proof

00:58:48.470 --> 00:58:51.560
beyond a reasonable doubt--

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:54.020
you think these
things are just going

00:58:54.020 --> 00:58:57.440
to be here forever and work.

00:58:57.440 --> 00:58:58.970
Wake up.

00:58:58.970 --> 00:59:02.420
Unless you fight
for them, people

00:59:02.420 --> 00:59:05.390
will say, well, be scared.

00:59:05.390 --> 00:59:06.800
Let's go punish them.

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:08.810
I didn't make this up.

00:59:08.810 --> 00:59:11.670
Go look at that ad
that President Trump,

00:59:11.670 --> 00:59:13.160
when he was a citizen, raised.

00:59:13.160 --> 00:59:14.826
I mean, this is what
he really believed,

00:59:14.826 --> 00:59:18.710
and he wasn't run out of
town because he said it.

00:59:18.710 --> 00:59:22.370
And I wish he would really
give it more thought.

00:59:22.370 --> 00:59:24.410
Nobody should be
considered hopeless

00:59:24.410 --> 00:59:29.169
in this kind of enterprise,
but if you want a democracy,

00:59:29.169 --> 00:59:30.710
you're going to have
to fight for it.

00:59:30.710 --> 00:59:33.510
If you want a fair
criminal justice system,

00:59:33.510 --> 00:59:35.390
you're going to have
to fight for it,

00:59:35.390 --> 00:59:39.830
because it is really imperiled
and under attack in many ways

00:59:39.830 --> 00:59:41.490
today.

00:59:41.490 --> 00:59:45.230
On the other hand, I'm
extremely optimistic myself

00:59:45.230 --> 00:59:50.630
that people such as yourselves
will look at this history,

00:59:50.630 --> 00:59:56.510
learn the lessons, bring to
bear real science, real science,

00:59:56.510 --> 01:00:03.050
in looking at how this system
can work and will protect

01:00:03.050 --> 01:00:07.220
the innocent and try our
very best to convict only

01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:08.788
those who committed the crimes.

01:00:15.080 --> 01:00:19.200
AUDIENCE: Thanks so much
for having this event

01:00:19.200 --> 01:00:21.770
and speaking here.

01:00:21.770 --> 01:00:23.780
I have a kind of
obvious question,

01:00:23.780 --> 01:00:26.090
which I can appreciate
as probably very

01:00:26.090 --> 01:00:27.890
difficult to answer.

01:00:27.890 --> 01:00:30.885
But is there any
research done to estimate

01:00:30.885 --> 01:00:32.510
the number of people
that are currently

01:00:32.510 --> 01:00:35.200
incarcerated that are innocent?

01:00:35.200 --> 01:00:36.049
How many are there?

01:00:36.049 --> 01:00:36.840
BARRY SCHECK: Yeah.

01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:40.950
That's a great question,
and people ask all the time,

01:00:40.950 --> 01:00:42.980
how many innocent
people are in jail?

01:00:42.980 --> 01:00:47.900
And the answer to that is,
well, if I knew, I'd tell you.

01:00:47.900 --> 01:00:51.410
We have huge backlogs at the
Innocence Project and innocence

01:00:51.410 --> 01:00:54.260
organizations across the
country of people claiming

01:00:54.260 --> 01:00:59.040
to be innocent that we're trying
to help all of our colleagues

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:00.380
and look at.

01:01:04.876 --> 01:01:08.730
A very good study
was done by Sam gross

01:01:08.730 --> 01:01:12.270
from the University
of Michigan Law School

01:01:12.270 --> 01:01:14.580
and I think Barbara O'Brien
from Michigan State that

01:01:14.580 --> 01:01:18.630
was published in the "National
Academy of Science Journal."

01:01:18.630 --> 01:01:21.180
Because in order to get a
handle on this question,

01:01:21.180 --> 01:01:23.880
you have to compare
apples to apples.

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:25.740
And I can tell
from your question

01:01:25.740 --> 01:01:28.380
that you understand the
difficulties of this.

01:01:28.380 --> 01:01:31.470
And we do have a class of
cases that we can look at.

01:01:31.470 --> 01:01:34.230
And that is capital
cases, because we

01:01:34.230 --> 01:01:35.850
have more data on those.

01:01:35.850 --> 01:01:37.740
We have more
transcripts, more of them

01:01:37.740 --> 01:01:40.830
gone through the court system.

01:01:40.830 --> 01:01:44.430
And then frankly, even though
capital representation isn't

01:01:44.430 --> 01:01:46.650
as good over the years
as it should have been,

01:01:46.650 --> 01:01:49.520
it is better ordinarily--
or more resources

01:01:49.520 --> 01:01:51.270
are devoted to it,
let's put it that way--

01:01:51.270 --> 01:01:52.950
than the average case.

01:01:52.950 --> 01:01:54.720
And what they've
been able to estimate

01:01:54.720 --> 01:01:58.260
is that the error
rate is at least 4%.

01:01:58.260 --> 01:02:02.670
And they were comparing capital
cases over a period of time,

01:02:02.670 --> 01:02:04.950
where they could look at
real evidence of innocence,

01:02:04.950 --> 01:02:07.258
compared to other cases.

01:02:07.258 --> 01:02:08.650
AUDIENCE: That's so high.

01:02:08.650 --> 01:02:08.950
BARRY SCHECK: What?

01:02:08.950 --> 01:02:10.350
AUDIENCE: That's
really, really high.

01:02:10.350 --> 01:02:12.150
BARRY SCHECK: Well,
that is absolutely--

01:02:12.150 --> 01:02:15.090
you're quite correct in
say-- the questioner said

01:02:15.090 --> 01:02:15.930
that's so high.

01:02:15.930 --> 01:02:19.300
And of course, it's high when
you consider that we have,

01:02:19.300 --> 01:02:22.410
what, something like that
more than two million people

01:02:22.410 --> 01:02:25.230
incarcerated in
the United States,

01:02:25.230 --> 01:02:27.180
more per capita than
just about anywhere.

01:02:27.180 --> 01:02:29.910
And then you look at a
lot of these place states,

01:02:29.910 --> 01:02:33.510
like Louisiana,
which has the highest

01:02:33.510 --> 01:02:37.200
per capita incarceration
plate of any jurisdiction

01:02:37.200 --> 01:02:39.450
on the planet.

01:02:39.450 --> 01:02:42.270
And that's one reason we get
all these innocent people out

01:02:42.270 --> 01:02:44.602
in Louisiana.

01:02:44.602 --> 01:02:45.810
There's plenty of them there.

01:02:45.810 --> 01:02:47.970
So the rate is very high.

01:02:47.970 --> 01:02:52.980
There's other data that is
very suggestive about this.

01:02:52.980 --> 01:02:57.510
When we first began doing
DNA testing, starting in 1989

01:02:57.510 --> 01:03:01.350
and moving forward,
and the FBI was

01:03:01.350 --> 01:03:03.780
one of the few
public agencies that

01:03:03.780 --> 01:03:07.680
would do it for state and
local law enforcement for free,

01:03:07.680 --> 01:03:10.230
they were finding
consistently when they

01:03:10.230 --> 01:03:14.010
had a suspect in a case, right?

01:03:14.010 --> 01:03:18.030
Which in theory meant that
there was some probable cause

01:03:18.030 --> 01:03:21.210
or reasonable basis for picking
somebody up, arresting them,

01:03:21.210 --> 01:03:23.460
charging them, and then
they would move forward

01:03:23.460 --> 01:03:25.200
with the DNA testing--

01:03:25.200 --> 01:03:29.970
that one third of the
time, the primary suspect

01:03:29.970 --> 01:03:32.470
was excluded by the DNA testing.

01:03:32.470 --> 01:03:38.550
So that is very, very
suggestive that the rate

01:03:38.550 --> 01:03:40.530
of innocent people
being convicted

01:03:40.530 --> 01:03:43.210
is much higher than
any of us ever thought.

01:03:43.210 --> 01:03:44.400
And that is the truth.

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:48.300
I think that the one thing
you'll find from our colleagues

01:03:48.300 --> 01:03:53.220
in the prosecution, we
get a lot of support

01:03:53.220 --> 01:03:55.020
from the International
Association

01:03:55.020 --> 01:03:56.940
of Chiefs of Police,
from policing people

01:03:56.940 --> 01:04:00.630
all across the country, because
police officers, when they

01:04:00.630 --> 01:04:02.492
go into it, they
didn't get into it

01:04:02.492 --> 01:04:04.200
and risking their
lives because they want

01:04:04.200 --> 01:04:05.880
to lock up the wrong person.

01:04:05.880 --> 01:04:09.360
They want to lock up the right
person and protect the public.

01:04:09.360 --> 01:04:13.140
| we need to make
that job easier.

01:04:13.140 --> 01:04:16.860
We need to bring more
science to bear on this.

01:04:16.860 --> 01:04:19.860
We need to change
those institutions,

01:04:19.860 --> 01:04:21.150
so we can get better at it.

01:04:21.150 --> 01:04:24.000
It's a very difficult
and imperfect enterprise.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:27.180
And we have to constantly
be improving the system.

01:04:27.180 --> 01:04:31.590
But there is no doubt-- that's
what DNA and the innocence

01:04:31.590 --> 01:04:36.000
movement proved, I think, to
everybody's satisfaction among

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:39.390
stakeholders in the
criminal court system--

01:04:39.390 --> 01:04:43.900
that there are far more innocent
people than anybody ever,

01:04:43.900 --> 01:04:46.290
ever, ever suspected.

01:04:46.290 --> 01:04:49.410
And we are still at the
beginning of this process.

01:04:49.410 --> 01:04:51.690
I mean, when we started
this 25 years ago,

01:04:51.690 --> 01:04:55.170
this is our 25th anniversary
of the Innocence Project.

01:04:55.170 --> 01:04:59.520
And you'll see "Time Magazine"
did a whole issue that you

01:04:59.520 --> 01:05:01.800
can find on this
on the newsstands

01:05:01.800 --> 01:05:06.000
right now, because it is
an important historical

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:09.420
and cultural and
political development

01:05:09.420 --> 01:05:11.550
to see an innocence movement.

01:05:11.550 --> 01:05:15.030
Everybody thought that
as more DNA testing

01:05:15.030 --> 01:05:17.580
was done at the
beginning of the case,

01:05:17.580 --> 01:05:20.560
right, that we'd all
go out of business.

01:05:20.560 --> 01:05:23.970
Well, the answer is, we have
more exonerations, which

01:05:23.970 --> 01:05:28.720
look at the National Registry
numbers, than ever before.

01:05:28.720 --> 01:05:30.990
And the DNA has
remained constant

01:05:30.990 --> 01:05:34.230
in terms of the
number of old cases.

01:05:34.230 --> 01:05:37.950
And even some new ones, where
the DNA wasn't done right,

01:05:37.950 --> 01:05:40.470
we've been able to
exonerate people.

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:45.750
But we now know more
about how innocent people

01:05:45.750 --> 01:05:51.990
get convicted and get better at
trying to correct these errors.

01:05:51.990 --> 01:05:53.770
So that's a very--

01:05:53.770 --> 01:05:55.790
you're right it's a
complicated question.

01:05:55.790 --> 01:05:58.820
If you put a gun to my head and
said, what's the error rate,

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:02.840
I'll go with the article in
"The National Academy of Science

01:06:02.840 --> 01:06:03.950
journal," at least 4%.

01:06:03.950 --> 01:06:06.217
AUDIENCE: So that's
like 100,000 people.

01:06:06.217 --> 01:06:07.800
BARRY SCHECK: Oh,
it's more than that.

01:06:07.800 --> 01:06:10.910
And in truth, I mean, guessing.

01:06:10.910 --> 01:06:12.770
But we don't like to guess.

01:06:12.770 --> 01:06:14.540
We like to bring
all the data that we

01:06:14.540 --> 01:06:16.460
can to bear on the problem.

01:06:19.700 --> 01:06:21.200
So I think that's it.

01:06:21.200 --> 01:06:23.344
And we thank you
very, very much.

01:06:23.344 --> 01:06:26.592
[APPLAUSE]

01:06:28.448 --> 01:06:30.660
And hope for your support.

01:06:30.660 --> 01:06:34.440
Anyone in the innocence
movement, go online--

01:06:34.440 --> 01:06:36.720
innocenceproject.org,
Innocent Network,

01:06:36.720 --> 01:06:41.660
any innocence organization in
your jurisdiction, and help us.

